          <msContents>
            <summary>Planetarium: opus de fabrica horarii magistralis. Written in a semi-currenthumanistic hand, 30 lines to a page. Some initials and headings in red, much faded. Illustrated with 59 pen-drawings of parts of the clock, etc.: of these, 33 are coloured. There are also many smaller illustrations of minior pieces of mechanism. The colourings are in water-colour and gold paint. Inside the lower cover is a 17th cent. pen and ink drawing, showing three men standing outside the door of a house, one bare-headed, holding a jug [?]. Fol. 1 (Text begins) et calculationis tedio ac si ad dictam horam fuerit cum tabulis operatus modicissima/et paruae curae si qua interueneit differentia uarietatis... 14, line 1 ...Fuit namque/huius temporis. scilicet. 1364. anno christi perfecto secundum tabulas alfonsi in fine ge/-minorum... 83v ... Et sic/eo situato reduc deorsum ut denticuli inzegnonsis reinserantur cum/sua rotula et in axicula reimpone cauillam sicque dimitte.//Factus est hic liber Anno Domini 1364. ut colligitur/ex principio pagine 14.</summary>
            <textLang mainLang="" source="IANA">Latin</textLang>
            <msItem n="1" xml:id="MS_248_1">
              <author>Dondis, Johannes de, 1318-1389</author>
              <title type="original">Dondis, Johannes de (1318-1389)</title>
              <title type="standard"/>
              <textLang mainLang="" source="IANA">Latin</textLang>
              <filiation>For an account of the Author and his clock, cf. Thorndike's [i]History of Magic and Experimental Science[/i], Vol. III, Chap. 24, pp. 740-741.</filiation>
              <filiation/>
            </msItem>
